This is the Package that is for sale: Mossberg Model 88, Maverick 12 ga.  Also included in the Sale Price is: Synthetic Stock and Forearm that came with the shotgun from the factory and Synthetic Pistol Grip and the Wood Stock and Wood Forearn mounted as shown. 

The Model 88 Maverick shotgun had a synthetic stock and forearm standard from the factory instead of nice wood. However, I purchsed the Wood Sock and Froearm and mounted them on the shotgun. I also purchsed the Synthetic Pistol Grip. Total Package as shown: New, Never Fired, Grips & Stocks Never Used.  

The Maverick is identical to the Mossberg 500 in every way except three....the safety is moved from the receiver to the trigger guard, the forearm is a one piece instead of the Mossberg steel tube, and the Maverick has a synthetic stock and forearm standard from the factory instead of nice wood. 

Those three things were cost cutting measures so Mossberg could market it as an economy line 500. Other than those three things, the Maverick 88 is identical to the Mossberg 500. They're made from the same parts on the same assembly lines as the Mossberg 500 and all accessories except the forearm are interchangeable.

This Model will last as long as any Mossberg 500 or Remington 870. It won't break or wear out if you don't abuse it. If in some way you manage to damage it, it can be repaired in five-ten minutes or less with replacement parts. 

A very good and versitile shotgun. It's inexpensive....it's not cheap.

Thompson Center Hawkens Muzzel Load Rifle -  New – Test Fired Only 

History
In  1815 Jacob Hawken established a gun shop in the village of St. Louis. Jacob’s brother, Samuel, joined him in 1822. The Hawken brothers established a reputation for manufacturing excellent Muzzleloading Rifles. Their claim to fame was the "plains rifles". The Plains Rifle was what their customers needed when they ascended the Missouri River in search of Beaver, a quality gun, light enough to carry all the time and capable of knocking down big targets at long range.

They called their Rifles "Rocky Mountain Rifles". Rifles Stamped “J&S Hawken St. Louis” were sought after throughout the rapidly expanding frontier among trappers and mountain men. In 1849 Jacob Hawken died and rifles were marked S. Hawken. A number of famous men were said to have owned Hawken Rifles, including: Jim Bridger, Kit Carson, Joseph Meek and Theodore Roosevelt.

Undoubtedly the most copied rifle in the history of firearms, the T/C Hawken was designed for the American shooter. This is a top quality firearm—every bit as fine as the one your great, great granddaddy carried across his saddle pommel or packed along on the wagon train. It captures the romance of the original but it is manufactured to standards of quality control that were unheard of in the early 1800’s. The proper use of the investment casting, improved methods of hardening parts and deep hole drilling, the use of continuous Magnaflux process to guard against imperfections in the steel itself coupled to our constant attention to min./max. tolerances is what allows us to offer a lifetime Warranty! Thompson Center arms manufacture the finest quality muzzleloading firearms available.

It has a double triggers; the rear trigger is a "set" trigger. When the rear trigger is pulled, the hammer does not fall but rather the action "sets" the front trigger, the front trigger becoming a "hair trigger," tripped with a light touch. When the front trigger is used without using the rear "set" trigger, it requires a firm pull.

title: For Sale:  1911A1 Remington Rand /Ithaca US Military World War II  45ACP Semi-Auto Handgun
location: Pagosa Springs Co, Colorado, United States
postcontent: 1911A1 Remington Rand /Ithaca US Military World War II  45ACP Semi-Auto Handgun. This sort of mix 'n match is very common with US military 1911s. After WWII there were mass inspection and rebuild programs both here and Europe. Pistols were stripped, inspected, and reassembled without regard to "matching parts." Remington Rand Slide with Short type 3 (REMINGTON RAND STRACUSE, N .Y. U.S.A.) On   Left Side and Small P on top of Slide  I have no way of dating the slide. Ithaca frame serial number NO512390 Small 0 with line underneath This late wartime production Ithaca has flat side Ithaca made grooved (serrated) hammer, stamped trigger, Keyes Fiber Co. plastic grips with the thin reinforcement rings (circles) around the grip screw holes. This gun has the proper serrated mainspring housing, thumb safety The inspection stamp of Frank J. Atwood "FJA" is located on the left hand side of the receiver behind the trigger. His stamps are found on both Remington Rand and Ithaca 1911A1s and  is stamped after finish. The ordnance Department  inspection mark on frame to the above the grip on right side is faint and there is  P then on slide below the magazine release. There is also a  factory inspection mark on the left side of trigger guard .If interested plese e-MAil me for detail pictures . WWW.coolgunsite .com is very good site with lots of detailed information on 1911A1’s The gun is in good shape showing metal wear and some marks on the bottom of magazine and on frame under trigger. title: For Trade:  Krestrel--Sniper Handheld Weather and Ballistics Meter with Night Vision
postcontent:
Works great for Shooting, Hunting or Fishing, brand new in the box
The Kestrel 4500 NV with Horus ATrag Ballistics combines Kestrel's flagship meter, the Kestrel 4500 with Night Vision, with Horus ATrag Ballistics software to bring you the first lightweight, hand-held tool to give you both comprehensive environmental data plus integrated aiming solutions. Kestrel Pocket Weather Meters and Horus Vision partnered to provide a powerful shooting tool that combines the critical environmental data and targeting software solutions required for precision shooting. 


 The Kestrel 4500 NV with Horus ATrag Ballistics allows you to load, customize and store multiple guns, rounds and targets. Target parameters include distance, angle, longitude, speed, direction and wind. Kestrel's highly accurate measuring and averaging of wind together with built-in digital compass for target bearing and wind direction assists in defining the target winds. The Kestrel 4500 NV with Horus ATrag Ballistics is available with Bluetooth technology, which allows you to communicate with your Kestrel wirelessly at a range of up to 30-feet, and maximize the battery life of your meter.
The Kestrel can measure in TMOA (true minute of angle), SMOA (shooter minute of angle), and MILs (milliradians).  The unit displays ballistic tables with data of the shot extending out to various distances (see Range Card on page 17 and 18 in the manual).  This Horus meter can provide ballistics solutions out to 4000 yards (or about 3700 meters). 



Once you’ve built the gun that you’ll be using (and you’re at the range of course), you need to enter the target range into the Kestrel, as well as the latitude (if you’re concerned about the coriolis effect), then either manually enter the wind or use the auto capture feature to capture the wind speed. 


The Bluetooth serves to connect the computer to the Kestrel if the user is interested in logging weather data (just like in the non-Horus version) and uploading to the computer, or the user can utilize the Gun Library software created by (and available from) Horus Vision.  This software will allow customers to build guns on their computers, download them to the Kestrel, or upload guns they’ve modified in the field.



Horus software that comes with the 4500 Atrag Ballistics is the civilian version.
